<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/54218760-steve-wilhite"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1458792241i/54218760._UX100_CR0,17,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/54218760-steve-wilhite">Steve Wilhite</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I also haven&apos;t seen any direct attributions, but I can&apos;t imagine that both Tim Burton and Neil Gaiman weren&apos;t heavily influenced by this book, among m<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I also haven't seen any direct attributions, but I can't imagine that both Tim Burton and Neil Gaiman weren't heavily influenced by this book, among many others in Bradbury's oeuvre. The possible connection to "Nightmare Before Christmas" actually struck me even before Moundshroud makes his entrance, when we're first introduced to Tom Skelton.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
