    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3008015114" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3008015114" />
    <a title="Michael Jandrok" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/66672731-michael-jandrok"><img alt="Michael Jandrok" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1561055227p2/66672731.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3008015114?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Jandrok" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Jandrok" href="/user/show/66672731-michael-jandrok">Michael Jandrok</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780553106107" href="/book/show/9440642-the-halloween-tree">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3008015114" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15403279249267393582">I have an idea that certain books have a time about them, a temporal space in which they can be savored for maximum impact and delight. Some authors give me that same sense. Even some GENRES appear to have a window of opportunity within the Wheel of the Year making them more appealing and instinctual when it comes down to choosing that next read off of that never dwindling TBR pile. Ray Bradbury is one of those authors for me, his general work seeming to compel me to pick him out as the summer b</span>
  <span id="freeText15403279249267393582" style="display:none">I have an idea that certain books have a time about them, a temporal space in which they can be savored for maximum impact and delight. Some authors give me that same sense. Even some GENRES appear to have a window of opportunity within the Wheel of the Year making them more appealing and instinctual when it comes down to choosing that next read off of that never dwindling TBR pile. Ray Bradbury is one of those authors for me, his general work seeming to compel me to pick him out as the summer begins to wane and that lovely time of Autumn begins to spill over the Veil, draped like some sheets in the attic used to cover all that beautiful, Gothic furniture and….. why is that door open? I could swear that it was closed only a few moments ago…..<br /><br />For the record, Bradbury isn’t the only author who evokes this sense of temporal SPACE. Shirley Jackson does it for me, too. As does Mary Stewart, Agatha Christie, and Charles Dickens. Plenty of other authors and books occupy other spaces with the year for me, and there are always plenty of other authors and books that can be read year-round with no sense of displacement. <br /><br />I have made it a Goodreads tradition to pick up some Bradbury sometime around late summer or early Autumn, his poetic voice speaking to me from that great beyond where surely his rockets to Mars still fly and his Illustrated Man is still looking for body space to add a new story to. This year I decided to take a visit to “The Halloween Tree,” that vast and wildly alive growth of pulp and woodstock set to forever guard and play companion to the equally vast and wildly alive house owned by its Master….yes, that one there, set off from the road, beckoning the child in all of up to try and creep just a little bit closer…..a little bit closer. Eight teenaged boys, mind you, but there are supposed to be nine. And there IS a ninth boy, though he only appears in shadows and sickness for a goodly portion of the book. So, nine teenaged boys it is, but just barely. For little do they know they are about to meet up with one of the archetypal guises of Death himself on this moonlit Halloween night.<br /><br />The boys have ransacked the Town Proper for as much of its candies and treats as they can carry. Now there is only one abode left to pillage. But beware! THIS house belongs to one Carapace Clavicle Moundshroud, a mysterious character who offers them a chance at something more interesting that just another piece of wrapped marzipan. The ninth boy appears briefly on the threshold of consciousness before being whisked away in the darkness on the night. The boys strike a deal with Moundshroud. They will travel with him this night to various other cultures, to various other ceremonies, in order to suss out the true meanings of Halloween. But before they set off, the magnificent Halloween tree must be lit. A thousand candlelit caricatures spring to fiery light one by one, leaving the most majestic candle to follow home in the history of the world. And they are off!!!<br /><br />Yeah, I do a crappy job of exposition, especially when I try to play at evoking a sense of the prose offered by the author. Geez, this is RAY BRADBURY we are talking about here. I could no more appreciate nor approximate his gifts as a writer as I could with ten times the meager talents I possess. And I love Bradbury, not just for his ability to evoke a sense of wonder, but to be able to fully communicate that sense in the form of the written word. “The Halloween Tree” is no exception to this formula. It is as poetic, as shimmering, and as MAJESTIC as you think it will be. As soon as that ninth boy is stolen by the night, the remaining eight lads make a pact with Moundshroud. They cleave adventure out of thin air and navigate the time stream to arrive at a number of different Halloweens at a number of different spaces, a number of different places, meant to open their eyes on the wide variety of death rituals that rule the night when the veil beyond life and death is at its most fragile. My personal favorites are the Egyptians, who designed their entire CULTURE to act as a sort of death cult. I also had fun with Bradbury and the boys down in Mexico, where Dia de los Muertos festivals rule in an uneasy alliance between the indigenous rituals of the Americas and the stolid Catholicism brought over by the Spaniards. <br /><br />Bradbury is less adept at telling the stories of the Druids and the folk customs of Dark Ages Europe. This really does not surprise me. Europe’s indigenous cultures were spread out and consisted of a mosaic of different traditions based on sympathetic magick. These loosely bound and inconsistent traditions would also be put to the boot heel of Christianity as it spread across Europe. Only traces of the “old” ways can be found these days, but they still create quite the story when something new turns up at an archaeological dig. <br /><br />THE PART WHERE MIKE GIVES YOU TOO MUCH PERSONAL INFORMATION. FEEL FREE TO SKIP IF YOU SO DESIRE: My interests with modern Paganism started me on the road to wanting become an archaeologist when I grew up. The problem is that I seem to have never grown up. Anyway, neo-Paganism in most of the world refers to what we will call Gardnerian Wicca. Gerald Gardner, self-taught archaeologist and a correspondent with Margaret Murry, took Murray’s extensive notes and theories and spliced them together with a dash of Aleister Crowley and a smidgen of Alan Watts in order to come up with a more modern update on the old European folk traditions. Now Gardner was a colorful dude, but he eschewed the flamboyance of Crowley and Church of Satan founder Anton LaVey, even though he borrowed a lot of ideas about the workings of magick from both men. The main point that I am trying to get across is that Druidic and folk traditions from Europe are to this day poorly understood and misrepresented to the public at large. <br /><br />Ack, I ruin good reviews that way. It’s okay to just tell me to just shut the hell up and get on with it already. Anyway, our poor ninth boy is indeed found by the end of the book, but to save him each one of the boys must make a critical decision that will deeply affect them as time goes by. This is the only spot in the book where the reader gets a shiver down the spine, as it is now fully apparent as to who Moundshroud actually IS. It’s a sinister moment, and it creeps up you but it’s also fully in tune with the novel as a whole. TRUE love, TRUE friendship, and TRUE commitment all require a sacrifice of some sort from us. And if we are willing to make that sacrifice too, then we will get our turn to stand before the mighty Halloween Tree, its candles blowing out now, the night breeze kicking things up a notch. Oh, but what a wonder to be there.<br /><br />“The Halloween Tree” clocks in at 160 pages, or so my Bantam Pathfinder edition says. Originally aimed at a juvenile audience, it was still a huge hit with adult Bradbury fans, too. Illustrated by longtime Bradbury collaborator Joe Mugnaini, this short novel should be read and read again every time the month of October rolls around. This is stone cold genius as only Ray Bradbury could present it to you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15403279249267393582" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


