<div id="review_2144818293" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2144818293" />
    <a title="aPriL does feral sometimes " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes"><img alt="aPriL does feral sometimes " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478243665p2/3409532.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2144818293?book_show_action=true">Oct 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="aPriL does feral sometimes " class="user" itemprop="url" name="aPriL does feral sometimes " href="/user/show/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes">aPriL does feral sometimes </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780553512700" href="/book/show/23743745-the-halloween-tree">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=magical-drama">magical-drama</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=literary">literary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=mythology">mythology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=teen-nerd">teen-nerd</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=paranormal">paranormal</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=children">children</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2144818293" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16737723428334585632">‘The Halloween Tree’ is a scary tale either meant for, or to be read to, little boys of eleven or twelve. The novel is about the imagery that different cultures from Egypt to Rome to the Middle Ages to Mexico have developed to represent Death through the ages. It is more poetry than prose, an Impressionist painting of history in words.<br/><br/>A young friend, Pipkin, has appendicitis and has been hospitalized. Usually he has led the friends trick ‘n treating on Halloween, but not this year. The usual gan</span>
  <span id="freeText16737723428334585632" style="display:none">‘The Halloween Tree’ is a scary tale either meant for, or to be read to, little boys of eleven or twelve. The novel is about the imagery that different cultures from Egypt to Rome to the Middle Ages to Mexico have developed to represent Death through the ages. It is more poetry than prose, an Impressionist painting of history in words.<br /><br />A young friend, Pipkin, has appendicitis and has been hospitalized. Usually he has led the friends trick ‘n treating on Halloween, but not this year. The usual gang of friends, eight boys, are worried, but they walk the streets to knock on doors for candy as if everything is normal. However, this year, what worries them is an unspoken question: what is Death? Will Pipkin be alright?<br /><br />The boys dare each other to knock on the door of the scariest house. Ooooooh! Mr. Moundshroud comes to the door. Oh oh. He only does <i>Tricks</i>!<br /><br />Hint: where did mummies, skeletons, witches, gargoyles, ghosts, and last but not least, cloaked Death with his scythe, come from? The boys weren’t asking, but Mr. Moundshroud is going to show them anyway...<br /><br />Happy Halloween!<br /><br />👻🎃💀👹🌜<br /><br />From page 20: <br /><br />“The stars they turn, the candles burn<br />And the mouse-leaves scurry on the cold wind bourne,<br />And a mob of smiles shine down on thee<br />From the gourds hung high on the Halloween 🎃 Tree.<br /><br />The smile of the Witch, and the smile of the 🐈,<br />The smile of the Beast, the smile of the 🦇,<br />The smile of the Reaper taking his fee<br />All cut and glimmer on the Halloween tree...”<br /><br />The title of the book and the vaguely nightmarish story is obviously a literary twist on the real “Tree of Evolution” developed by scientists, only instead the book is about a history of the imagination of human culture in pondering Death. Death is, of course, the source material of the Halloween holiday.<br /><br />The book is reminiscent of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35570936.The_Night_before_Christmas_or_A_Visit_from_St__Nicholas" title="The Night before Christmas or A Visit from St. Nicholas by Clement C. Moore" rel="nofollow noopener">The Night before Christmas: or A Visit from St. Nicholas</a> except it has a Halloween theme and Great Literature values. <br /><br />I noticed from GR reviews the book is heavy going for many modern readers, probably because of its mix of literary prose and actual poetry. I guess it is helpful to the child reader if parent readers have some education in history, literature, poetry and religion in order to explain and understand this book to youths. The only cure for any blank incomprehension you, gentle reader, may experience in reading this ‘children’s’ book is to read a lot more classics and history books.<br /><br />So. If you are a literary educated parent with a nerdy son, I recommend this novella. Do I sound like a sniffy pointy-headed elitist? Can’t help it. It is what it is. I read a lot.<br /><br />My copy of the book had terrific illustrations by Gris Grimly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16737723428334585632" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


